    (1322,'There is no school equal to a decent home and no teacher equal to a virtuous parent.',1),
    (1323,'What difference does it make to the dead, the orphans, and the homeless, whether the mad destruction is wrought under the name of totalitarianism or the holy name of liberty or democracy?',1),
    (1324,'You must be the change that you wish to see in the world.',1),
    (1325,'Live simply, that others may simply live.',1),
    (1326,'Among the many misdeeds of the British rule in India, history will look upon the act depriving a whole nation of arms as the blackest.',1),
    (1327,'Seven Deadly Sins  Wealth without work Pleasure without conscience Science without humanity Knowledge without character Politics without principle Commerce without morality Worship without sacrifice.',1),
    (1328,'God forbid that India should ever take to industrialism after the manner of the west... keeping the world in chains. If [our nation] took to similar economic exploitation, it would strip the world bare like locusts.',1),
    (1329,'Strength does not come from physical capacity. It comes from an indomitable will.',1),
    (1330,'Man often becomes what he believes himself to be. If I keep on saying to myself that I cannot do a certain thing, it is possible that I may end by really becoming incapable of doing it. On the contrary, if I have the belief that I can do it, I shall surely acquire the capacity to do it even if I may not have it at the beginning.',1),
    (1331,'Silence becomes cowardice when occasion demands speaking out the whole truth and acting accordingly.',1),
    (1332,'Whatever you do will be insignificant, but it is very important that you do it.>',1),
    (1333,'You may never know what results come of your actions, but if you do nothing, there will be no results.',1),
    (1334,'Breach of promise is a base surrender of truth.',1),
    (1335,'The simplest acts of kindness are by far more powerful then a thousand heads bowing in prayer.',1),
    (1336,'Earth provides enough to satisfy every man''s needs, but not every man''s greed.',1),
    (1337,'To believe in something, and not to live it, is dishonest.>',1),
    (1338,'I abhor vivisection with my whole soul. All the scientific discoveries stained with innocent blood I count as of no consequence.',1),
    (1339,'Whenever you are confronted with an opponent. Conquer him with love.',1),
    (1340,'Action expresses priorities.>',1),
    (1341,'The expert knows more and more about less and less until he knows everything about nothing.',1),
    (1342,'I will not let anyone walk through my mind  with their dirty feet.',1),
    (1343,'Gentleness, self-sacrifice and generosity are the exclusive possession of no one race or religion.',1),
    (1344,'Seek not greater wealth, but simpler pleasure; not higher fortune, but deeper felicity.',1),
    (1345,'An eye for eye only ends up making the whole world blind.',1),
    (1346,'There is more to life than increasing its speed.',1),
    (1347,'Live as if you were to die tomorrow. Learn as if you were to live forever.>',1),
    (1348,'To my mind, the life of a lamb is no less precious than that of a human being.',1),
    (1349,'First they ignore you, then they ridicule you, then they fight you, and then you win.',1),
    (1350,'I cannot conceive of a greater loss than the loss of one''s self-respect.',1),
    (1351,'Let the first act of every morning be to make the following resolve for the day:  - I shall not fear anyone on Earth.  - I shall fear only God.  - I shall not bear ill will toward anyone.  - I shall not submit to injustice from anyone.  - I shall conquer untruth by truth. And in resisting untruth, I shall put up with all suffering.',1),
    (1352,'Liberty and democracy become unholy when their hands are dyed red with innocent blood.',1),
    (1353,'Nonviolence and truth (Satya) are inseparable and presuppose one another. There is no god higher than truth.',1),
    (1354,'A small body of determined spirits fired by an unquenchable faith in their mission can alter the course of history.',1),
    (1355,'Freedom is not worth having if it does not connote freedom to err. It passes my comprehension how human beings, be they ever so experienced and able, can delight in depriving other human beings of that precious right.',1),
    (1356,'Unity to be real must stand the severest strain without breaking.',1),
    (1357,'Earth provides enough to satisfy every man''s need, but not every man''s greed.',1),
    (1358,'The future depends on what you do today.>',1),
    (1359,'Keep your thoughts positive because your thoughts become your words.  Keep your words positive because your words become your behavior.  Keep your behavior positive because your behavior becomes your habits.  Keep your habits positive because your habits become your values.  Keep your values positive because your values become your destiny.',1),
    (1360,'It''s the action, not the fruit of the action, that''s important. You have to do the right thing. It may not be in your power, may not be in your time, that there''ll be any fruit. But that doesn''t mean you stop doing the right thing. You may never know what results come from your action. But if you do nothing, there will be no result.',1),
    (1361,'I object to violence because when it appears to do good, the good is only temporary; the evil it does is permanent.',1),
    (1362,'Faith... must be enforced by reason.... When faith becomes blind it dies.',1),
    (1363,'Your beliefs become your thoughts,  Your thoughts become your words,  Your words become your actions,  Your actions become your habits,  Your habits become your values,  Your values become your destiny.',1),
    (1364,'You can chain me, you can torture me, you can even destroy this body, but you will never imprison my mind.',1),
    (1365,'A man is but the product of his thoughts. What he thinks, he becomes.',1),
    (1366,'Remember that all through history, there have been tyrants and murderers, and for a time, they seem invincible. But in the end, they always fall. Always.',1),
    (1367,'An eye for an eye only ends up making the whole world blind.',1),
    (1368,'Where there is love there is life.',1),
    (1369,'Each night, when I go to sleep, I die. And the next morning, when I wake up, I am reborn.',1),
    (1370,'All those who try to go it sole alone, <br />Too proud to be beholden for relief, <br />Are absolutely sure to come to grief. <br />',2),
    (1371,'Ah, when to the heart of man\r\nWas it ever less than a treason\r\nTo go with the drift of things,\r\nTo yield with a grace to reason,\r\nAnd bow and accept the end\r\nOf a love or a season?',2),
    (1372,'Talking is a hydrant in the yard and writing is a faucet upstairs in the house. Opening the first takes all the pressure off the second.',2),
    (1373,'The land was ours before we were the land’s. <br />She was our land more than a hundred years <br />Before we were her people. <br />',2),
    (1374,'I shall set forth for somewhere, <br />I shall make the reckless choice <br />Some say when they are in voice <br />And tossing so as to scare <br />The white clouds over them on, <br />I shall have less to say, <br />But I shall be gone. <br />',2),
    (1375,'Poetry begins in delight and ends in wisdom.',2),
    (1376,'They cannot scare me with their empty spaces Between stars—on stars where no human race is. I have it in me so much nearer home To scare myself with my own desert places.',2),
    (1377,'Have I not walked without an upward look <br />Of caution under stars that very well <br />Might not have missed me when they shot and fell? <br />It was a risk I had to take—and took. <br />',2),
    (1378,'I have been one acquainted with the night. <br />',2),
    (1379,'I never dared to be radical when young <br />For fear it would make me conservative when old. <br />',2),
    (1380,'Home is the place where, when you have to go there,\r\nThey have to take you in.',2),
    (1381,'A bank is a place where they lend you an umbrella in fair weather and ask for it back when it begins to rain.',2),
    (1382,'A diplomat is a man who always remembers a woman’s birthday but never remembers her age.',2),
    (1383,'I never dared be radical when young\nFor fear it would make me conservative when old.',2),
    (1384,'The trees that have it in their pent-up buds\nTo darken nature and be summer woods -',2),
    (1385,'How many things have to happen to you before something occurs to you?',2),
    (1386,'First there’s the children’s house of make believe, <br />Some shattered dishes underneath a pine, <br />The playthings in the playhouse of the children. <br />Weep for what little things could make them glad. <br />',2),
    (1387,'A poem… begins as a lump in the throat, a sense of wrong, a homesickness, a lovesickness. It is never a thought to begin with. It is at its best when it is a tantalizing vagueness. <br />',2),
    (1388,'The woods are lovely, dark and deep. <br />But I have promises to keep, <br />And miles to go before I sleep, <br />And miles to go before I sleep. <br />',2),
    (1389,'I had a lover''s quarrel with the world.',2),
    (1390,'Don’t join too many gangs. Join few if any. <br />Join the United States and join the family— <br />But not much in between unless a college. <br />',2),
    (1391,'A successful lawsuit is the one worn by a policeman.',2),
    (1392,'The world is full of willing people; some willing to work, the rest willing to let them.',2),
    (1393,'But strictly held by none, is loosely bound <br />By countless silken ties of love and thought <br />To everything on earth the compass round, <br />And only by one’s going slightly taut <br />In the capriciousness of summer air <br />Is of the slightest bondage made aware. <br />',2),
    (1394,'If society fits you comfortably enough, you call it freedom.',2),
    (1395,'Love is an irresistible desire to be irresistibly desired.',2),
    (1396,'Being the boss anywhere is lonely. Being a female boss in a world of mostly men is especially so.',2),
    (1397,'If we couldn''t laugh we would all go insane.',2),
    (1398,'Like a piece of ice on a hot stove the poem must ride on its own melting…. Read it a hundred times; it will forever keep its freshness as a metal keeps its fragrance. It can never lose its sense of a meaning that once unfolded by surprise as it went.',2),
    (1399,'Forgive, O Lord, my little jokes on Thee <br />And I’ll forgive Thy great big one on me. <br />',2),
    (1400,'Poets are like baseball pitchers. Both have their moments. The intervals are the tough things.',2),
    (1401,'In three words I can sum up everything I''ve learned about life — It goes on.',2),
    (1402,'The snake stood up for evil in the Garden. <br />',2),
    (1403,'But yield who will to their separation, <br />My object in living is to unite <br />My avocation and my vocation <br />As my two eyes make one in sight. <br />Only where love and need are one, <br />And the work is play for mortal stakes, <br />Is the deed ever really done <br />For Heaven and the future’s sakes. <br />',2),
    (1404,'The best way out is always through.',2),
    (1405,'The heart can think of no devotion Greater than being shore to the ocean- Holding the curve of one position, Counting an endless repetition.',2),
    (1406,'I go to school the youth to learn the future.',2),
    (1407,'Now no joy but lacks salt <br />That is not dashed with pain <br />And weariness and fault; <br />I crave the stain <br />Of tears, the aftermark <br />Of almost too much love, <br />The sweet of bitter bark <br />And burning clove. <br />',2),
    (1408,'Two roads diverged in a wood, and I — I took the one less traveled by, And that has made all the difference.',2),
    (1409,'The afternoon knows what the morning never suspected.',2),
    (1410,'I am not a teacher, but an awakener.',2),
    (1411,'And nothing to look backward to with pride, <br />And nothing to look forward to with hope. <br />',2),
    (1412,'O hushed October morning mild,\nBegin the hours of this day slow,\nMake the day seem to us less brief...\nRetard the sun with gentle mist;\nEnchant the land with amethyst...',2),
    (1413,'Happiness Makes Up in Height for What It Lacks in Length.',2),
    (1414,'Any eye is an evil eye <br />That looks in on to a mood apart. <br />',2),
    (1415,'No tears in the writer, no tears in the reader.',2),
    (1416,'By working faithfully eight hours a day you may eventually get to be boss and work twelve hours a day.',2),
